  "game_explanation": "All three players start with 10 RED and 10 GREEN chips. GREEN is common-value at $0.50 for everyone. RED is privately more valuable to Badger ($0.80) than to Otter or Goose ($0.30 each). No one knows others’ exact values, but everyone knows that values can differ, and that GREEN is safely worth $0.50 to all.\n\nIncentives: Badger is strongly motivated to accumulate RED chips and is more willing to part with GREEN, since each RED is worth far more to her than to the others, while GREEN is only $0.50 for all. Otter and Goose are symmetric in valuation: both value RED low (0.30) and GREEN higher (0.50). So, from an omniscient perspective, efficient trades transfer RED from Otter/Goose to Badger, and GREEN from Badger to Otter/Goose, at exchange rates that lie between their private values. But because players only know their own values and face uncertainty about others, they must infer others’ valuations from observed offers and acceptances.\n\nStrategically, Otter and Goose will tentatively try small GREEN-for-RED trades early, probing whether others value RED more. Because they also have empathy and cooperation orientations in their profiles, they’re likely to prefer mutually beneficial deals rather than purely exploitative ones. Otter, with high cooperation orientation, may start with a relatively generous or symmetric-looking proposal to test willingness to trade. Goose, with higher cognitive reflection and numeracy, is likely to be more calculating about rates once he observes behavior.\n\nBadger, who values RED highly, gains from acquiring RED for less than $0.80 of GREEN per RED, but must be careful not to reveal just how much she values RED or she may face tougher prices. Her search willingness is high, so she is likely to actively propose trades rather than passively wait. She may initially offer seemingly fair but modestly favorable terms (e.g., 1 GREEN for 2 RED) and adjust depending on how Otter and Goose respond.\n\nUncertainty centers on two things: (1) how much others value RED relative to GREEN, and (2) which counterpart, if both accept, will actually trade, since multiple acceptances trigger a random recipient. This randomization makes it risky for a proposer to set extremely favorable terms that could attract both others simultaneously; still, with only three rounds and three turns per round, players may not put much weight on sophisticated signaling and instead focus on obvious win–win trades.\n\nOver three rounds, as players witness who accepts or declines which offers, they update their beliefs: repeated willingness by Badger to buy RED with GREEN signals a high Badger RED value; reluctance by Otter/Goose to trade GREEN for single RED at near-even terms signals that RED is low-value to them. This belief updating should push the group toward more efficient patterns: RED gradually consolidating with Badger and GREEN moving toward Otter and Goose, though frictions (limited rounds, uncertainty, and random partner selection) may prevent perfect efficiency. The likely observed game is a sequence of modest RED-for-GREEN trades, with some early exploratory offers declined and later offers more closely targeting mutually obvious gains.",
