r prices (roughly one GREEN per RED or slight discounts), (2) growing recognition that someone is willing to sell RED at fairly low prices (badger), and that at least one player values RED highly (peacock), and (3) attempts by otter either to secure modest gains or at least avoid ending worse off. The random mechanism when multiple recipients accept also influences behavior: senders tend to design offers that will likely attract exactly one counterpart rather than both, to avoid price escalation or unexpected partner matches. By the end of Round 2, the most likely configuration is that some of badger’s RED has moved toward peacock (directly or via otter), generating surplus, while otter ends with roughly balanced holdings and modest profit from one or two small trades.",
