  "game_explanation": "This three-player, three-round bargaining game features one privately high-value red holder (whale), one very low red valuer (zebra), and one high red valuer (swan). All share a known, fixed value for green ($0.50 each), but only whale and swan know that red is valuable to them ($0.80 each) while zebra only knows red is almost worthless to her ($0.10). From a social-surplus perspective, the efficient pattern is that zebra should sell away her red chips to whale or swan in exchange for greens, since she values green more than red while they value red more than green. However, uncertainty about others' red values and the random recipient rule when multiple players accept make it risky for proposers to write very generous offers: if both potential partners accept, the actual counterpart is chosen randomly, so you can't directly target the low-red-value zebra. Given their risk/uncertainty profiles, whale (high uncertainty aversion, moderate numeracy) will likely start cautiously by offering modest, clearly profitable red-for-green trades, trying to induce zebra to reveal herself as a red seller without making it attractive for swan to compete. Zebra (very risk averse, analytically strong) has a clear incentive to offload red in return for green at almost any reasonable rate, but must also be wary of giving away too much to either whale or swan if she suspects they might have very high red values. Swan (medium risk and cooperation, lower cognitive reflection) also wants to buy red from zebra but must compete with whale under the constraint of random matching. Strategic tension arises because whale and swan are potential competitors for zebra's red, yet occasionally they may inadvertently trade valuable red between themselves if they misjudge each other's valuations. Across the three rounds, as accepted offers appear, everyone infers a bit more about others' valuations and willingness to trade, but the game is too short for full learning; players instead rely on simple heuristics: zebra tends to propose selling red for green at favorable but not extreme prices, whale tends to avoid selling red and focuses on modest red-for-green purchases, and swan alternates between opportunistic buying from zebra and probing trade offers that could be profitable if accepted by the right counterpart. Many plausible offers will be declined because potential partners either suspect adverse selection, view the rate as unfavorable, or fear that accepting alongside another player will result in a random, less-profitable match.",
