ry few green), turtle might reject due to fairness or misestimation of others' values.\n\nUncertainty also arises because whale and swan do not know whether turtle’s red is high or low value. They might tentatively test the market with offers that still give turtle a visible gain in green chips, while not overpaying. They may gradually infer from accepted or rejected offers that turtle’s red value is on the low side. Meanwhile, turtle does not know if whale/swan value red more or less than he does; he will infer from willingness to give up green how much they might value red. The game includes simultaneous responses and random partner selection when multiple players accept, so proposers cannot target specific partners in a given turn, which slightly weakens collusive or reciprocal strategies.\n\nGiven the personas, we expect:\n- Turtle to actively try to trade away red for green at modest, cooperative-looking terms, often willing to accept generous red-for-green deals from whale and swan. He will likely anchor on simple ratios (e.g., 1 red for 1 green or slightly better for himself in green terms) and may not aggressively optimize.\n- Whale, more cautious and uncertainty-averse with medium cooperation, will test the waters with slightly conservative offers: a few green for several red, but not extreme. She will likely accept any offer from turtle that gives her red at an implicit price below $0.50 per red (e.g., giving 1 green for 2 or more red).\n- Swan, less numerate and somewhat more risk-seeking (lottery-loving), is likely to follow simpler heuristics and be more willing to accept offers that create visible chip-count gains in red even if marginal pricing is imperfect. She may be more flexible on ratios but still avoid trades that clearly reduce the number of green chips too sharply.\n\nAcross three rounds, there is enough time for a few mutually beneficial trades but not enough for a rich learning process. Most of the action likely occurs early as players probe