nistically accept deals from Dog when surplus is clear.\n\nStrategically, because each proposal can be accepted by either non-sender and acceptance is resolved randomly if multiple players accept, proposers must design offers that are attractive enough to at least one partner but preferably skewed so that the most desirable counterparty is more likely to accept. However, they don’t directly control which partner they get when both accept, so they often shape offers that one target finds clearly profitable and the other finds only marginal or unattractive.\n\nOver three rounds (nine total proposal turns), players gradually learn about each other’s preferences. Early offers will tend to be conservative, probing the environment with small quantities and obvious win-win trades (e.g., Dog selling low-value red for green). As the game proceeds, especially if earlier proposals reveal that someone is willing to trade red or blue, the others may attempt more aggressive or exploitative trades (for example, Ram trying to buy red cheaply from Dog, or Butterfly moving green into high-valued color holdings). The finite horizon (3 rounds) and the absence of future games reduces the value of reputation; players are primarily focused on immediate personal gains, not fairness norms.\n\nGiven the personas, we forecast relatively cooperative but self-interested behavior: proposals are generally designed to be acceptable and mutually beneficial, with some players (Butterfly and Ram) exploiting their better numeric understanding to engineer slightly asymmetric trades in their favor. Dog’s high empathy and cooperation make her inclined to accept many clearly beneficial trades, but her uncertainty aversion may cause her to reject complex or highly asymmetric offers that she doesn’t fully understand in time. The result is a sequence of mostly incremental, surplus-creating trades with modest reallocation of red and blue chips from Dog to Ram and Butterfly, while Dog accumulates additional green and possibly some safer mix of chips.",
