encourages offers that are just attractive enough that at least one person will accept, but not so generous that both accept with high probability.\n3. Time and round structure: There are three rounds, each with one proposal turn by Alligator, then Otter, then Tiger. Players anticipate only nine total proposal opportunities (three per player). Early in the game, they may experiment more to learn others’ valuations; by later rounds, they may be more willing to pay up or concede to lock in value.\n4. Persona-based tendencies: Otter is more uncertainty averse and analytical; likely to prefer straightforward, transparent trades involving green and blue at roughly fair-seeming rates, showing reluctance to accept obscure red-based deals early. Tiger is somewhat more risk-tolerant and flexible, willing to accept advantageous red deals when they look good. Alligator, older and somewhat numerate but with low value for red, is strongly motivated to unload red for almost anything decent and to accumulate blue and green.\n\nUnder these forces, we expect:\n- Alligator to use early proposals trying to exchange red (low private value) for green or blue, possibly offering attractive terms to get quick acceptance and signal willingness to trade.\n- Otter to probe blue-for-red/green tradeoffs carefully, trying to bring in more blue (valued at 1.00) while not giving away too much green.\n- Tiger to capitalize on cheap red coming from Alligator, and then later potentially trade some red/green to acquire blue from Alligator or Otter if prices are good.\n\nThe forecasted game below reflects one coherent path: Alligator gradually offloads red in exchange for green and some blue; Otter and Tiger split the available opportunities, with Otter ending as the bluest player and Tiger amassing red while keeping a solid green base. Most trades involve at least one common-value leg (in green) to reduce perceived risk. No player ever sees the true payoff structure, so each step is locally rational under incomplete information rather than globally optimal under full information.",
