ners they would be comfortable trading with, while ensuring that no unintended overpay occurs if a less-preferred counterpart unexpectedly accepts. Over the three rounds, players see evolving chip positions and accepted offers, gradually inferring others’ valuations (e.g., that dog eagerly acquires RED/BLUE, that cat is willing to pay for PURPLE). This learning feeds back into subsequent proposals: early offers are more exploratory and conservative, while later ones can be more tailored, using observed behavior as noisy signals about private values. However, the finite horizon (3 rounds, 9 total proposals) and the inability to coordinate within a single turn limit complex signaling; players will generally aim for clearly positive expected value trades from their own perspective, exploiting perceived mispricings (e.g., cat selling RED/BLUE cheaply, dog selling PURPLE cheaply, badger using PURPLE as a sweetener) while preserving GREEN as a safe anchor unless substantially compensated.",
