nd update beliefs; later rounds they must lock in surplus-improving trades.\n\nGiven the personas, all three are relatively cooperative and averse to uncertainty, with moderate to high numeracy and financial literacy. This suggests offers will often be conservative, avoiding extreme exploitation; players will tend to seek clearly positive expected-value trades based on their own valuations, making incremental improvements rather than complex multi-step gambles. We forecast a sequence where early proposals probe others’ willingness to part with specific colors (especially RED and PURPLE), later converging on trades that move low-value chips (for the responder) toward those who value them more, especially via GREEN or BLUE as a bridging asset. However, incomplete information and random recipient selection will lead to some declined offers and a mix of bilateral gains that are not perfectly efficient from the group’s perspective.",
