  "game_explanation": "All players start symmetric in chip counts (10 of each color) but asymmetric in how much they privately value red/blue/purple. Green is common value at $0.50 for everyone, so it serves as a safe, easy-to-understand medium for trade. Dog-red-9959 has the strongest preferences for purple ($0.90) and red ($0.60) and thus has the highest marginal gains from acquiring those colors. Otter-yellow-9944 especially values purple ($0.60) and is relatively weak on blue and red ($0.30 each). Bear-blue-8468 values blue and red at $0.60 and $0.50 respectively, and purple least at $0.30. This creates natural surplus: bear is relatively happy to give up PURPLE for BLUE or RED, otter is relatively happy to give up BLUE/RED for PURPLE or GREEN, and dog is especially eager to acquire PURPLE and reasonably eager to acquire RED, while having only moderate interest in BLUE.\n\nHowever, each player only knows their own valuations, so they must infer others’ preferences from observed offers and acceptances. The short horizon (3 rounds, 9 total proposal turns) increases urgency: there is limited time to learn and coordinate, and any trade risk (like accidentally giving away something highly valued by a partner) tends to be weighed more heavily, especially by players who are more uncertainty-averse. Given the personas, otter and bear are both quite uncertainty-averse, so they are likely to prefer trades that are clearly beneficial in terms of absolute chip counts or involve GREEN, which they know all value the same. Dog is more cognitively reflective, numerate, and less uncertainty-averse, so he is more likely to calculate approximate expected values from trades and take advantage of opportunities, even when they reveal some of his preferences.\n\nAcross the game, we expect early offers to be somewhat conservative and centered on GREEN and simple 1-for-1 or 2-for-1 structures that look safe. As players see which offers get accepted (especially at what chip ratios and colors), they update their beliefs about what others might value. Dog, as the strongest analyst, is likely to make and accept trades that concentrate PURPLE and RED with him, even if that means parting with BLUE or some GREEN. Otter and bear will look for trades that give them modest gains without exposing them to much downside; they will likely accept offers involving GREEN when the chip count or composition clearly improves their bundle. Competition between otter and dog for PURPLE chips creates some friction: both would like PURPLE, but dog is willing to pay more in value terms, so trades that move PURPLE toward dog are often efficient even if they look superficially even in chip counts. Because acceptance is simultaneous and, when multiple accept, random, proposers must design offers that are profitable regardless of which responder accepts.\n\nThe resulting likely pattern: gradual movement of PURPLE and RED chips toward dog, BLUE chips drifting toward bear, and GREEN chips used selectively as a safe balancing currency. Some mutually beneficial trades will be missed because of risk aversion and limited information, but we still expect a few efficient reallocations by the later rounds as players become more confident about others’ preferences from the emerging trade history.",
