 try to avoid trades that obviously make her worse off relative to her own chip values.\n\nStrategic uncertainty is driven by incomplete information: each player only knows their own red/blue/purple values and must infer others’ preferences from offers. Proposals also face a coordination uncertainty: multiple responders can accept, and the actual partner is chosen randomly, so proposers cannot target specific counterparts. That encourages offers that would be attractive to at least one other player but not so generous that both always accept, to reduce the risk of giving a good deal to the “wrong” partner.\n\nOver three rounds, each player has three proposal turns. The short horizon makes each decision relatively myopic: there is little incentive to wait for dramatically better opportunities, but risk-averse players might still pass on marginal trades. Ram is incentivized to acquire BLUE and PURPLE, mostly by spending her nearly worthless RED and possibly some GREEN. Goose wants more BLUE and perhaps RED if the price in GREEN is favorable, but will be cautious about giving up GREEN. Butterfly, with near-flat values, will tend to be attracted to simple, seemingly fair rate trades (e.g., 1 GREEN for 1 RED or BLUE), especially early when uncertainty is highest.\n\nLikely dynamics: early in Round 0, Ram tries turning RED into GREEN with a modest, plausibly fair rate, to test willingness without scaring off risk-averse partners. Goose then may try to exchange some GREEN for RED, reflecting his higher RED value relative to PURPLE and rough parity with GREEN, targeting Butterfly as the more accepting partner. Butterfly will respond to both offers based on whether the terms improve her own value per chip or at least don’t harm her. In later rounds, players update beliefs: if someone eagerly trades away a color, others infer that chip is low-value to them, which can motivate more aggressive requests. However, because there are only nine total proposal turns and no communication, many potentially efficient trades will never occur, and risk-aversion and uncertainty may lead to declined proposals that would be mutually profitable under full information.",
