  "game_explanation": "This three-player chip game creates classic bilateral bargaining tensions under incomplete information. All players start with 10 of each color (RED, BLUE, PURPLE, GREEN). GREEN is common-value at $0.50 for everyone, so green trades are only about reshuffling risk and chip composition, not increasing group surplus. The private values for the other colors are sharply misaligned: zebra highly values BLUE ($1.00) and PURPLE ($0.90) and dislikes RED ($0.10); swan values neither BLUE nor PURPLE much (both ≤ $0.40) and is relatively neutral between RED and PURPLE ($0.40 each); dolphin moderately values everything, with RED ($0.60), PURPLE ($0.70), and BLUE ($0.50) all positive but none extreme. From an omniscient perspective, the biggest efficiency gains come from moving low-value chips away from those who value them least (e.g., zebra’s RED at $0.10) toward those who value them more (dolphin at $0.60, swan at $0.40), while sending back higher-value chips (e.g., zebra’s BLUE or PURPLE) from low-value holders like swan.\n\nHowever, each player only knows their own payoffs and sees only proposals/acceptances, so they must infer others’ values from behavior. Zebra, older and relatively risk-averse with decent numeracy, is likely to make conservative, value-focused offers, trying to offload RED and acquire BLUE/PURPLE, but not giving up many of these high-value chips unless the gains are clear. Swan, very numerate and cognitively strong with high cooperation orientation, is likely to reason strategically about others’ valuations and design offers that slightly favor himself but are clearly profitable for a partner, especially using the fact that GREEN is a safe medium value. Dolphin, with lower numeracy but high cooperation orientation and high empathy, is likely to accept deals that are visibly better than keeping her current chips, even if not perfectly optimized, and might sometimes accept moderately unbalanced deals if they look roughly fair.\n\nThe main uncertainty each player faces is how much the others value specific colors: zebra doesn’t know if RED is worthless for everyone or secretly valuable; swan doesn’t know if anyone really wants BLUE; dolphin doesn’t know how extreme zebra’s dislike of RED is. Early proposals reveal information: if someone eagerly trades away a color, others infer that chip is probably low-value for that proposer; if they keep refusing to part with a color at attractive rates, others infer it’s high-value. Because acceptance is simultaneous and the recipient is random when multiple accept, proposals must be profitable no matter which non-sender accepts. This randomization discourages very targeted offers and encourages deals that could work for either partner (e.g., trading away your clearly low-value color for something you at least somewhat like). Over three short rounds, there is little time for elaborate signaling; players will likely aim for straightforward, modestly favorable trades that offload their worst color in exchange for a safer or more valuable one. Swan is the most likely to orchestrate clear win–win trades, dolphin the most likely to accept decent-looking offers, and zebra the most likely to stick to offers where he gains obvious value without complex speculation.",
