 more present-focused and may be more opportunistic, sometimes over- or under-reacting to perceived deals, but still responsive to obvious gains. Elephant is analytically strong and cooperative-leaning, likely to spot and accept clear surplus-creating trades, especially those that improve holdings of RED and BLUE while shedding PURPLE. Across three short rounds, players have limited time to learn about each other, so early trades will likely be simple, small, and focused on very weak vs. very strong colors (e.g., moving PURPLE out of Elephant’s hands and RED out of Turtle’s), with later rounds possibly escalating slightly once some signals about others’ willingness to trade have been observed.\n\nOverall, we forecast modest reallocation: Turtle trying to turn RED into GREEN or PURPLE, Elephant trying to turn PURPLE into RED or BLUE, and Hamster acting as a flexible middle player who might trade RED away for PURPLE or BLUE and sometimes provide GREEN in exchange for high-valued colors. Not all possible gains from trade will be realized due to information frictions, random recipient selection, and a short horizon of only three rounds.",
